<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7311&amp;p=71887#p71887"><![CDATA[
Yeah, what Dwedit said it good.  So you probably can use a normal cheat finder to find and test stuff (or maybe even Game Action Replay codes), but then you'll have to back up bit and find the opcode in ROM that's effecting the change.  That requires minimal proficiency in 6502 assembly, you can get help with that around here.<br /><br />The Game Genie, however can only patch 3 bytes of ROM.  I seem to remember someone had chained 2 of them together and it worked, but I could be wrong.<br /><br />What could be fun is to change what rights to the $4001 and $4005 registers.  That would change the audio a lot by enabling frequency sweeps.  In fact, if you play most Capcom games with a Game Genie, this already happens.  Because GG uses the sweep regs, and Capcom didn't initialize them.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Fri Dec 24, 2010 11:50 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
