<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7311&amp;p=71874#p71874</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7311&amp;p=71874#p71874"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Glitching A/V using GameGenie - help decoding]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7311&amp;p=71874#p71874"><![CDATA[
With a game genie, you can use an emulator with a debugger to plan out what your 3 codes will be.  Some ASM skill needed here, but if you can use a cheat finder, you can find out interesting RAM addresses, then set data breakpoints for those.  Then change the asm code to something else.<br /><br />I've gotten into creating my own Game Genie codes, for example, I made a few codes for Dragon Warrior 4 to remap the "Try Out" AI control mode into "You control the party" mode, then let you re-enable AI control as well.<br /><br />And 8000-FFFF is always the ROM, not RAM.  0000-07FF is the system RAM, and 6000-7FFF is cartridge RAM found on some games.<br /><br />If you just want to screw up the graphics, then let the game sit out and get all dusty <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=53">Dwedit</a> — Fri Dec 24, 2010 8:55 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
