<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7311&amp;p=71871#p71871</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7311&amp;p=71871#p71871"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Glitching A/V using GameGenie - help decoding]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7311&amp;p=71871#p71871"><![CDATA[
2CB3 isn't the address, the address is ACB3.<br />I'm guessing that they actually use the "most significant" bit to indicate whether the code has a compare value or not.  One setting has an 8-letter code that includes a compare value, the other setting has a 6-letter code without compare value, but both point at the same address.<br /><br />So it's like the address is always OR-ed with 8000.<br />I don't think a game genie will mess with the "cartridge RAM area" of 6000-7FFF, even for the few games that map ROM there.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=53">Dwedit</a> — Fri Dec 24, 2010 8:38 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
